div.p:
               Thirdly, I neither do believe, nor can find, that the Quakers say, Christ's Body, either was, or is, of an earthy perishing Nature (as F. B. hath frequently charged it upon Isaac Pennington, and consequently upon the Quakers Ministers, for his sake, but that the Flesh and Blood of our Nature (and as 'tis in us) is of an Earthly perishing Nature, whereas Christs Flesh saw no Corruption, it did not Corrupt; 
                  Psa. 16.10. Act. 2.31 and 13.37. And therefore it were a very great Ignorance


and Absurdity for any to say, that his Body (which is chang'd and glorified) is of an Earthy and perishing Nature, he being Ascended into Glory. This is answer'd in our Charitable Essay, p. 4. and Unrefuted by F. B. And I still charge it upon him as a Lie, that the Quakers say Christ's Body, either was, or now is, of a perishing Nature.
